body:
Its not a regression.

```
test: ~'@{@{pre}-color}'
```

comes out as

```
test: @{original-color};
```

basically we don't allow multi lookups in strings. The solution is to do this

```
 @var: "@{pre}-color";
 @color: color(@@var);
```

I can't imagine alot of uses cases for this (this is our first request I believe), so I am not going to just implement it - things get complicated otherwise.

I have improved the error reporting for the color function so that it errors on non-colour strings being passed to it.

@lukeapage I'm not quite following you. You mention:

>    test: ~'@{@{pre}-color}'
> 
> comes out as
> 
>    test: @{original-color};
> 
> basically we don't allow multi lookups in strings.

But when I run it straight out (as I note in my first example) it comes out correctly as

```
color: #ff0000; 
```

Which would seem to me that it does fine with "multi lookups in strings" in that case. It is just in the `color()` function that it does not do fine (and maybe that is what you mean, that inside that function you do not allow multi lookups). However, I still cannot seem to get it to work with the solution you noted. This...

```
@original-color: #ff0000;
@pre: original;

.test() {
  .test {
    @var: "@{pre}-color";
    color: color(@@var);
  }
}

.test();
```

Produces... 

> Syntax error: error evaluating function `color`: argument must be a string
> .test();

Ok, the error about must be a string is because it is already a color - you do not need the color function.. e.g.

```
@original-color: #ff0000;
@pre: original;

.test() {
  .test {
    @var: "@{pre}-color";
    color: @@var;
  }
}

.test();
```

or

```
@original-color: "#ff0000";
@pre: original;

.test() {
  .test {
    @var: "@{pre}-color";
    color: color(@@var);
  }
}

.test();
```

or if you don't know if its a string or a color

```
@original-color: #ff0000;
@pre: original;

.test() {
  .test {
    @var: "@{pre}-color";
    @col: @@var;
    color: color("@{col}");
  }
}

.test();
```

regarding interpolation working twice.. you are right.. I simplified your example. e.g.

```
@original-color: #ff0000;
@pre: original;

.test {
  color: ~'@{@{pre}-color}';
}

.test() {
  .test {
    color: ~'@{@{pre}-color}';
  }
}

.a {
.test();
}
```

note how when it isn't a mixin it doesn't double interpolate. I think when it is a mixin the string is being evaluated twice, once when it is in the mixin and once when it is in its final location, magically giving you double interpolated strings. when you add the color function it is being evaluated once for the color function. so its a bug that it works at all..

I can fix that and will have to think about whether we should support double interpolation.

